You Tell Me ?

42 & going Strong! Heard this on the way to work and had to play it all day long.  Easily Top 10 shows of all time.  Second set mastery, culminating in an epic Dew!   ....and some say it never happened.....

My Preferred Version We could argue for hours about the relative merits and demerits of the Seamons and Usborne matrix mixes of this famous show.

The truth is that you can't go wrong with either one.  The Dan matrix (SHNID 35086) also packs a mean punch if you want an alternate.

However, as far as I'm concerned, Usborne's mix has just a little bit extra, a little bit that Seamons is lacking.  I think the clarity comes from the second AUD that Usborne used, the Rob Berger AUD (SHNID 117027).

This is most notable in the transition between Lazy Lightning and Supplication.  There's a somewhat psychadelic feel to the transition, almost like you're entering into a warp zone in Super Mario Bros.  It's not quite as obvious and sudden as it is in the Seamons matrix, which makes this my preferred version.

You can't go wrong, of course.  The matrix recordings for this show are simply outstanding.

Note that the official version includes patches from a different 1977 show; perhaps another Deadhead can remind us which show it is.  It doesn't matter, of course, because the official version is missing all the fun audience noise — particularly the guy screaming "Play America's Favorite Song: Truckin'!" throughout the second set.

Not all matrix recordings are greater than the sum of their parts.  This show, however, really should only be enjoyed in matrix format.
